**Description**:

If a sequence in a batch has a zero length we never set the previous value so end up reading uninitialized data. We correctly zero out anything that used the uninitialized data when producing the final output so it's harmless, however it's fairly trivial to handle nicely so do that instead of creating a valgrind suppression.

title: NCHWc: Enable Conv/Add fusion for stride=2 convolutions
body:
**Description**:
Update the NCHWc graph transformer to allow Conv/Add fusion for convolutions where stride=2.

**Motivation and Context**
The NCHWc graph transformer has logic to do mini-shape inferencing to allow symbolic dimensions to be carried through the graph. This fills in a gap where the ONNX shape inferencing code doesn't create new symbolic variables through the graph. This optimization was added to handle models like yolov3 which have variable height/width inputs.

This logic has been extended to also handle convolutions where stride=2, in order to optimize Faster-RCNN from the model zoo, which also has a variable height/width input. Detecting this pattern lets the transformer avoid multiple reorder ops and also enables Conv/Add fusion saving more time.

For the zoo faster-RCNN model: before the change, 155ms, after the change 149ms (-o 2 takes 180ms).

title: Remove memory copy between TensorRT and CUDA
body:
This PR is to remove memory copy between TensorRT and CUDA.
Current TensorRT execution provider is used as a CPU device. When a graph is partitioned between TensorRT and CUDA execution providers, memory copy occurs. The overhead could be significant if there are many partitions in the graph.
The major changes are,
1. TensorRT runs as a CUDA logic device as it should be.
2. Adapt to PR#1268 to use IDataTransfer interface on physical device level.
3. Upgrade TensorRT to v5.1.5.0, TensorRT container to v19.06 and ONNX-TensorRT parser to branch 5.1.

title: move some optimizers to level1
body:
**Description**: Move 3 transformers to level 1 where they really belong

**Motivation and Context**
- Level1 Optimizers are the semantics preserving optimizations like node eliminations, node fusions (which fuse nodes into existing onnx nodes). Even after applying level1 transformer we still have a valid onnx graph which can be executed by any onnx runtime as well as any execution provider of ort. (Where as level2 and l3 optimizations are execution provider specific transformations which alter onnx graph in more complex ways than l1 optimizers)

- Initially we made an exception for ConvAddFusion, ConvMulFusion and ConvBNFusion and added them as level2 optimizers because they are not compatible with training. But it turns out training scenario is more complicated than we had originally anticipated and will need more work to handle it properly. In light of this moving these transformers to their correct level.

- Another reason for making this change now is quantization. We want to enable only the fusions which are not EP specific. This is because for quantization scenario we want both the quantization script and the model to be Execution provider agnostic.

title: Quantization and calibration
body:
**Description**: Calibration script that drives quantization of models.

**Motivation and Context**
- Current quantization of models support is limited to "static" changes of the models to replace "quantizible" [!] operators with their quantized counterparts, regardless of inputs.  The script included in this PR adds a "calibration loop" that, runs a model, collects metrics on the output of the "quantizable" operations/layers to determine the best range to quantize, and feeds the results of these range calculations to the existing quantizer.

Please NOTE:  This script makes two assumptions, that are largely unmet in the codebase and require external dependencies:
* the model to be quantized has been modified, decorating the "quantizable" nodes with a "debug" operator that allows the tracing of the output
* the modified model is run through a modified version of the WinML Model Runner.

Strictly, it should be possible to provide the desired functionality making only one of the dependencies above (i.e., running a modified model on a vanilla runtime, or running an unmodified model on an instrumented runtime).   This PR aims to serve as a basis of such development.

title: General performance testing tooling improvements
body:
**Description**: 
Various changes to aid performance testing
 - Add access to parent node from a subgraph so details from that node can be used
 - Default to level 3 optimization for onnxruntime_perf_test
 - Add code to create Concurrency Visualizer markers so it's easy for anyone to use that tool. 
   - Disabled by #define.
 - Add support for parallel requests to onnxruntime_perf_test
   - use threadpool with one thread per concurrent request
   - keep all threads running until all requests are done 
     - previously issued n concurrent requests, waited for all threads to be done, and repeated which means you're always returning to a state where there are no requests being processed by ORT before new ones are issued
   - issue the specified number of requests (-r parameter value) without multiplying by the number of concurrent requests.
 - When statistics are requested write them to std::cout as well as the output file so they're easily viewed
 - Add overall time value
   - when issuing concurrent requests this is meaningful

**Motivation and Context**
General changes based on recent performance testing needs

title: Minor perf improvements.
body:
**Description**: 
- Reduce calls to std::vector::size() in IExecutionFrame and NodeIndexInfo
  - Cache a few vector sizes which are frequently used in validity checks
    - Values don't change, and doing so makes it 2 instructions instead of 10
  - Remove an unnecessary check in IExecutionFrame
    - add a check to the ctor so we guarantee it's unnecessary
  - ~0.025% in ssd_mobilenet
- Reserve memory for the vectors in BroadcastIterator
  - saves reallocs if more than one value is added
    - but rare with the mlperf models for multiple values to be added so benefit is limited
      - looked like it would be more of a saving prior to discovering we tend to only add a single value 
  - slight tweak to the Broadcaster ctor code to make it more readable


**Motivation and Context**
Tail end of the simpler potential performance improvements coming of out the mlperf model analysis. The changes provide some benefit, but it isn't significant for those models.

title: Adding ability to record intermediate graph outputs
body:
Calibration can be used to improve quantization techniques, adding reduced-precision computation for neural networks while retaining high accuracy without retraining. `calibrate.py` adds ReduceMin and ReduceMax nodes to all Conv and MatMul nodes in a loaded ONNX model and ensures their outputs are stored as part of the graph output, extracts intermediate output values after inference, and returns a dictionary mapping added node names to average (ReduceMin, ReduceMax) values as input to `quantize.py`. Example usage:
```
python calibrate.py --model_path=<'path/to/model.onnx'> --data_set_path=<'path/to/data/folder'> --calib_mode='naive'

title: Optimize Fence checking performance
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
For majority of nodes, we do not need to do fence check. Instead, we only need to do FenceCheck for CPU<->GPU mem sync node, and its parent and children node. But we pay the Fence check cost for every single node and every single input and output.

This change will minimize the Fence check to only do it when necessary.
**Motivation and Context**
Minimize fence check cost. This is a replacement of PR 1500
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
This is required to improve ORT performance for lightweight model.

title: Let mlas use session thread pool
body:
**Description**: 
1. Let mlas use session thread pool
2. Remove onnxruntime_USE_MLAS cmake option
3. Remove the win32 thread pool code inside mlas

mlas will:
1. use ort thread pool if it get passed in
2. use openmp if the threadpool parameter is nullptr
3. run single threaded if the threadpool parameter is nullptr and openmp is disabled.

Mlas got the threadpool pointer from InferenceSession.

**Motivation and Context**
Let mlas use session thread pool, so that we can fully control the threads.

To avoid deadlock,  for each session, onnxruntime may at most have 3 thread pool instances:
1. session thread pool, for mlas. Controlled by session option
2. parallel executor thread pool
3. lstm thread pool, just for lstm

Before this change, we have 4: the avoid three and a windows thread pool.

title: Fix incorrect box offset computation in NMS op
body:
**Description**: 
The `boxes` tensor in NMS is of shape [batch_size, num_boxes, 4]. So we don't need to multiply by `num_classes` in order to compute box offset.

This was not captured by any test case, because to trigger an incorrect box offset computation, we need both batch_size > 1 and num_classes > 1 (didn't have such a test case). Even then, it takes a very specific combination of `iou_threshold`, `box coordinates`, and `box scores` to trigger an overall test case failure by selecting wrong boxes (hard to write a test case that fails without this change and succeeds (as expected) with this change).

**Motivation and Context**
Resolve #1610

title: Adding smooth averaging mode for calibration

Enabling various calibration modes:

- `naive`: taking the minimum of all ReduceMin values and the maximum of all ReduceMax values across images for each added node (code contained [here](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/1588))

- `smooth`: taking a weighted average of ReduceMin and ReduceMax values, where weights are based on the volumes of the general clusters these values fall into (code contained in this PR, and details about the algorithm used are contained in [this README](https://github.com/agnikumar/onnxruntime/tree/agnikumar/calibration/onnxruntime/python/tools/quantization))

title: MLAS: add U8U8 MatMul operation
body:
**Description**:
Implement the first round of changes for quantization inside MLAS. This adds a MatMul operation for U8xU8=S32 for x86/x64 processors.

**Motivation and Context**
This implements a version of U8xU8=S32 MatMul that works for SSE2/AVX2/AVX512BW/AVX512VNNI for Windows and Linux/OSX. The API is single-threaded in this iteration. This is enough to start plugging into the runtime in place of gemmlowp.

AVX1 systems could go faster by enhancing the existing SSE2 based kernel to use more registers, or implement SSE4.1 special case kernels, or go all the way and do AVX1 kernels. That can come later. x86 systems only have SSE2 kernels for now but could also implement AVX2 later if needed.

This change also implements the .hidden fix for the NCHWc assembly kernels to avoid reloc errors when using -fPIC and building Linux shared libraries. Several helpers were meant to be internal only and .hidden keeps them from showing up in the export table.

title: Add non-standard data type serialization mechanism
body:
**Description**
This PR enables us to serialize datatypes that at are not ONNX datatypes.

**Motivation and Context**

AutoML will introduce a few new datatypes such as Table that are eventually will become candidates to ONNX standardization. However, the standardization process sometimes takes too long and we want to be able to test models that have ONNX-like automl operators that are not yet standard and operate on our custom datatypes and have a proof of concept.

This change enables us to introduce new datatypes into a our local copy of the protobuf and save serialized models under the disguise of Opaque datatypes so we can testrun those models and compare expected outputs with the actual output.s

This PR still makes use of ONNX interned strings such as opaqu(domain_string, name_string) but it intercepts string to TypeProto and vice versa mapping requests so we put our custom datatype proto and our MLDataType where appropriate.

title: Fix issue that cudnnRNNForwardInferenceEx doesn't support 0 sequence in the bathes
body:
Fix issue that cudnnRNNForwardInferenceEx doesn't support 0 sequence in the bathes

Solution:
Reset the 0 sequence to 1 for the bathes before call the cudnnRNNForwardInferenceEx, has a array to track the batch id which has 0 sequence. Once get the result, call a CUDA kernel to mask on the output using the batch id tracked in the array.
